It contains

* the public OCaml interface (`blockscic.mli`);
* the C/‑C++ stub file (`blockscic_stubs.cpp`);
* a short “how it works” commentary that explains the design decisions that keep the hot loop fast.

You can drop the three pieces into a normal OCaml library directory, add the
`-lblocksci` (or whatever library you need) flag to the `ocamlc/ocamlopt`
command line, and you will have a usable OCaml API that lets the user supply a
callback that is executed for **every** block in a chain of ~800 M entries.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1. Public OCaml interface (`blockscic.mli`)

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   blockscic.mli –  OCaml bindings for the BlockSci C++ iterator
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** Abstract type that represents a single BlockSci block.  The value
    is a custom block that holds a pointer to a C++ ``Block`` object.
    The object is freed automatically by a finaliser, but the user may
    call {!release} explicitly if they want to free it earlier. *)
type block

(** {1  Accessors – cheap read‑only view of a block} *)

val height    : block -> int
(** Height (i.e. block number) in the chain. *)

val hash      : block -> string
(** 32‑byte block hash, returned as a 64‑character hex string. *)

val timestamp : block -> float
(** Unix timestamp of the block (seconds since epoch). *)

val tx_count  : block -> int
(** Number of transactions contained in the block. *)

(** {1  Initialisation} *)

val init : string -> unit
(** Initialise the library with the path to the BlockSci database
    (normally the directory that contains the ``chain`` file).  Must be
    called once before any other function. *)

(** {1  Iteration – the hot path} *)

val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
(** Iterate over **all** blocks in the chain, invoking the supplied OCaml
    callback for each block.  The callback receives a *fresh* [block] value
    on every iteration – the underlying C++ ``Block`` object is copied, so
    the callback can safely keep a reference to the value without it being
    overwritten by the next iteration.

    The implementation calls the callback directly from the C++ iterator,
    without building an intermediate OCaml list, so the loop runs at
    native C++ speed (apart from the inevitable OCaml callback overhead). *)

val iter_blocks_raw :
  (height:int -> hash:string -> timestamp:float -> tx_count:int -> unit) -> unit
(** A faster variant when the user only needs a few primitive fields.
    Instead of allocating a custom OCaml block, the stub extracts the four
    fields and calls the callback with a *tuple of arguments* (implemented
    with ``caml_callback3``).  This eliminates the per‑iteration allocation
    of a custom block and can be noticeably faster for tight analytics. *)

(** {1  Lifetime management} *)

val release : block -> unit
(** Explicitly free the C++ object wrapped by a [block] value.
    Normally unnecessary – the finaliser will do the job when the OCaml
    value becomes unreachable – but it can be useful to free memory early
    inside a long‑running loop. *)
```

